## 5. Data Flow: Chat Conversation

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant U as User
    participant FE as Frontend (chat.js)
    participant API as FastAPI (/api/chat)
    participant SVC as ChatService
    participant GEM as Gemini 2.5 Flash

    U->>FE: Types message + hits Enter
    FE->>FE: Render user bubble, push to history[]
    FE->>FE: Show typing indicator

    FE->>API: POST /api/chat<br/>{message, history[]}
    API->>SVC: generate_response(ChatRequest)

    SVC->>SVC: Build history with<br/>SYSTEM_DESIGN_PROMPT prefix
    SVC->>GEM: start_chat(history) → send_message(msg)
    GEM-->>SVC: AI response text

    SVC-->>API: ChatResponse {response, timestamp}
    API-->>FE: 200 JSON

    FE->>FE: Hide typing indicator
    FE->>FE: formatMarkdown(response)
    FE->>FE: Render AI bubble, push to history[]
    FE->>FE: Set status "Connected"

    U->>U: Reads AI response
```

### Key Details

1. **System Prompt**: The AI is primed with a `SYSTEM_DESIGN_PROMPT` that instructs it to behave as a "senior software architect" focused on HLDs, LLDs, flowcharts, and architecture diagrams
2. **History Management**: The frontend maintains `conversationHistory[]` in memory. On each request, it sends the entire history (minus the current message) so Gemini has full context
3. **Graceful Degradation**: If `GEMINI_API_KEY` is not set, the service returns a helpful error message with setup instructions instead of crashing
4. **No Canvas Mutation**: The chat currently does NOT modify the canvas. It only provides architectural guidance. The user manually acts on suggestions

---

## 6. Data Flow: Design Operations (Backend-Synced Canvas)

```mermaid
sequenceDiagram
    participant U as User
    participant CY as Cytoscape Canvas
    participant FE as canvas.js
    participant API as FastAPI (/api/design)
    participant SVC as DesignService
    participant REPO as DesignRepository
    participant FILE as project_design.json

    Note over U,FILE: === Initial Load ===
    FE->>API: GET /api/design/state
    API->>SVC: load_document()
    SVC->>REPO: load()
    REPO->>FILE: Read JSON
    FILE-->>REPO: Raw JSON
    REPO-->>SVC: DiagramDocument (validated)
    SVC-->>API: DiagramDocument
    API-->>FE: 200 JSON
    FE->>CY: cytoscape({elements: [nodes, edges]})

    Note over U,FILE: === User Adds a Node ===
    U->>CY: Clicks "Add Node" button
    CY->>FE: addNode(x, y)
    FE->>API: POST /api/design/operations<br/>[{type: "add_node", node: {...}}]
    API->>SVC: apply_operations(request)
    SVC->>SVC: Validate unique ID
    SVC->>SVC: Append node to document.nodes
    SVC->>SVC: version++, update timestamp
    SVC->>REPO: save(document)
    REPO->>FILE: Write JSON
    REPO-->>SVC: Saved document
    SVC-->>API: ApplyOperationsResponse
    API-->>FE: 200 JSON
    FE->>CY: cy.add(normalizeNode(node))
    FE->>U: showToast("Node added")

    Note over U,FILE: === User Deletes a Node ===
    U->>CY: Selects node + presses Delete
    CY->>FE: deleteSelected()
    FE->>API: POST /api/design/operations<br/>[{type: "delete_node", node_id: "n5"}]
    API->>SVC: apply_operations(request)
    SVC->>SVC: Verify node exists
    SVC->>SVC: Remove node + CASCADE delete connected edges
    SVC->>REPO: save(document)
    REPO->>FILE: Write JSON
    SVC-->>API: ApplyOperationsResponse
    API-->>FE: 200 JSON
    FE->>CY: cy.$(':selected').remove()
    FE->>U: showToast("1 item(s) removed")
```

### Why This Pattern Matters

> [!TIP]
> This is an **optimistic update with backend validation** pattern:
> 1. Frontend sends the operation to the backend **first**
> 2. Backend validates (unique IDs, node existence, etc.)
> 3. If valid → persists to JSON, returns success
> 4. Frontend **then** updates the local Cytoscape graph
> 5. If the backend rejects → the canvas stays unchanged, user sees an error toast
>
> This ensures the JSON file and the canvas are **always in sync**. The backend is the single source of truth.

