## 10. Summary: End-to-End User Flow

Here's what happens when a user opens the app and starts designing:

```mermaid
graph TD
    A["User opens localhost:5173"] --> B["Vite serves index.html"]
    B --> C["main.js runs on DOMContentLoaded"]
    C --> D["setupChat() checks /api/health"]
    C --> E["setupCanvas() calls GET /api/design/state"]
    C --> F["setupSettings() binds all controls"]
    
    D --> G{"Backend healthy?"}
    G -->|Yes| H["Status: Connected ✅"]
    G -->|No| I["Status: Offline ⚠️"]
    
    E --> J["Cytoscape renders nodes + edges"]
    
    J --> K{"User action?"}
    K -->|"Add/Edit/Delete Node"| L["POST /api/design/operations"]
    K -->|"Connect Nodes"| L
    K -->|"Ask AI Question"| M["POST /api/chat"]
    K -->|"Change Settings"| N["Local Cytoscape style update"]
    K -->|"Export JSON"| O["Download local file"]
    
    L --> P["Backend validates + persists"]
    P --> Q["Canvas updates locally"]
    
    M --> R["Gemini generates response"]
    R --> S["Chat bubble rendered"]

    style A fill:#1a1a2e,stroke:#c4a882,color:#e8e4df
    style J fill:#16213e,stroke:#c4a882,color:#e8e4df
    style P fill:#0f3460,stroke:#c4a882,color:#e8e4df
    style R fill:#0f3460,stroke:#c4a882,color:#e8e4df
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Key architectural insight**: The chat and canvas are currently **independent features**. The AI advises on system design, but the user manually creates the diagram. The planned evolution is to have Gemini generate structured operations that automatically update the canvas—bridging the gap between conversation and visual design.
